body:
If you pass a `Serialize` argument that does not produce any values (for example, an empty `Vec`) to `RequestBuilder.query()`, it results in a URL that ends in "?". Here is a test that shows the behavior:

https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=1647711889f5df31a99edbe18ce59256

Fundamentally, I find it strange that reqwest would generate such URLs, since it's never useful to have the extra ? at the end if it's not followed by any query parameters. It also makes it harder for me to write integration tests, because I have to explicitly encode the ? in the expected path for the request, even though it doesn't belong there.

Of course, you can just not call `query()` if you don't have any parameters, but that makes the `RequestBuilder` a lot more awkward to use. Here's my use case:

I want to write this:
```rust
let results: Vec<SearchResult> = client
    .get(&url)
    .headers(headers)
    .query(&self.get_query_params())
    .send()?
    .json()?;
```
In my case, `get_query_params()` may or may not return parameters, depending on the state of the system.

But instead I have to write something like this:
```rust
let mut request = client.get(&url).headers(headers);

let params = self.get_query_params();
if params.is_some() {
    request = request.query(&params);
}

let results: Vec<SearchResult> = request.send()?.json()?;
```
